--- DESIGN-AGENTS SESSION ---

COACH: Presented two-tier mental model before interrogation. Tier 1 Strategic
agents plan/coordinate/sequence but do not write code. Tier 2 Implementation
agents are doers with narrow deep context. Context boundary decisions ARE
architectural decisions.

---

COACH Q1: What Tier 1 strategic roles does this project need?

COACH recommendation: Three roles — Product Owner (user stories, success
criteria, scope arbitration), Architect (pipeline shape, API contracts, SQLite
design, synthesizes implementation agent assessment reports into prioritized
improvement plan), Project Manager (sequences work, identifies parallelism,
fans tasks to implementation agents).

PARTICIPANT: This model seems reasonable and logical. Let us continue.
[confirmed]

---

COACH Q2: What Tier 2 discipline agents does this project need?

COACH recommendation: Four — Backend Engineer (app.py, Flask routes, SSE,
export handler), Frontend Engineer (app.js, index.html, full SPA), Data
Engineer (db.py, SQLite schema, FTS5, indexes, thread-safety), AI Pipeline
Engineer (agents.py exclusively — all 9 agent classes, tool definitions, model
constants, agentic tool loop, parallelism).

PARTICIPANT: Yes this is a solid model. [confirmed]

---

COACH Q3: Are there technology specialist agents needed?

COACH initial recommendation: Okta/Identity Specialist for OIDC and LiteLLM.

PARTICIPANT: I do not know if it will be just an Okta specialist. I would call
them an integration specialist as they will maintain Auth, Integrations to
other resources including MCPs and their associated resources (Google
workspace, Slack and more).

COACH: Good refinement adopted. Integration Specialist owns: Okta OIDC
(Authorization Code + PKCE), LiteLLM proxy config (llm.atko.ai, SSL bypass,
model naming, key format), MCP server connections (Google Workspace, Slack,
Salesforce, Highspot, future additions), .env bootstrap pattern. Scoped to
integration pattern not specific tool — durable as integrations grow.

---

COACH Q4: What does each agent need to know and NOT know?

COACH presented context boundary table covering all 8 agents with explicit
Needs and Must NOT columns. Key boundaries: Backend does not touch agents.py
or integration specifics. AI Pipeline Engineer owns agents.py exclusively.
Integration Specialist does not touch business logic or DB schema. Frontend
talks to API only, does not know backend implementation.

PARTICIPANT: These boundaries are logical. [confirmed]

---

COACH Q5: What is the first task sequence?

COACH initial recommendation: Tracer bullet upload to export touching all
agents, with parallel workers after Architect API contract exists.

PARTICIPANT: Considering the code has been built, I would ask the current
agents to assess their respective areas of code based on the plan, then come
back with their assessment and recommendations to improve and/or change code
and plan. Run some in parallel.

COACH: Participant refinement adopted as first task sequence.
Parallel wave 1 (simultaneous): AI Pipeline Engineer audits agents.py,
Backend Engineer audits app.py, Data Engineer audits db.py, Frontend Engineer
audits app.js + index.html, Integration Specialist audits auth + LiteLLM +
.env + MCP readiness.
Sequential after wave 1: Architect receives all 5 reports, synthesizes into
prioritized improvement plan with rationale. PM receives plan, sequences tasks
into next parallel wave with dependency map.

